.SH "NAME"
Getopt::EX::Func \- Function call interface
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 1
\&  use Getopt::EX::Func qw(parse_func);
\&
\&  my $func = parse_func(...);
\&
\&  $func\->call;
.Ve
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This module provides the way to create function call object used in
Getopt::EX module set.
.PP
If your script has \fB\-\-begin\fR option which tells the script to call
specific function at the beginning of execution.  You can do it like
this:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    use Getopt::EX::Func qw(parse_func);
\&
\&    GetOptions("begin:s" => $opt_begin);
\&
\&    my $func = parse_func($opt_begin);
\&
\&    $func\->call;
.Ve
.PP
Then script can be invoked like this:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    % example \-Mfoo \-\-begin \*(Aqrepeat(debug,msg=hello,count=2)\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
In this example, function \f(CW\*(C`repeat\*(C'\fR should be declared in module
\&\f(CW\*(C`foo\*(C'\fR or in start up rc file such as \fI~/.examplerc\fR.  Actual
function call is done in this way:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    repeat ( debug => 1, msg => \*(Aqhello\*(Aq, count => \*(Aq2\*(Aq );
.Ve
.PP
As you can notice, arguments in the function call string is passed in
\&\fIname\fR => \fIvalue\fR style.  Parameter without value (\f(CW\*(C`debug\*(C'\fR in
this example) is assigned value 1.
.PP
Function itself can be implemented like this:
.PP
.Vb 8
\&    our @EXPORT = qw(repeat);
\&    sub repeat {
\&        my %opt = @_;
\&        print Dumper \e%opt if $opt{debug};
\&        for (1 .. $opt{count}) {
\&            say $opt{msg};
\&        }
\&    }
.Ve
.PP
It is also possible to declare the function in-line:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    % example \-Mfoo \-\-begin \*(Aqsub{ say "wahoo!!" }\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
Function \f(CW\*(C`say\*(C'\fR can be used because the function is executed under
\&\f(CW\*(C`use v5.14\*(C'\fR context.
